"""
original | Isaiah | 9-13 | python3 scripts/zc-original-isaiah-9-13.py

Key translation decisions:
- Isa 9:6: Four throne-names (Wonderful Counselor etc.); shalom as "peace/wholeness";
  the MKT retains "Prince of Peace" keeping the traditional reading
- Isa 9:7: olam ("everlasting") / tsedaqah ("righteousness" carrying social justice);
  "no end" to peace vs. "increase" — MKT follows the Hebrew
- Isa 10:15: axe/saw metaphor for Assyrian pride — instrument vs. user
- Isa 11:2: ruach (Spirit) seven-fold attributes — Spirit of wisdom, understanding, etc.
- Isa 11:4: ruach of his mouth = breath of his lips = the word as weapon
- Isa 12:2: YHWH/yeshuah — "the LORD, the LORD himself, is my strength and my song;
  he has become my salvation" — the divine name Yah in the yeshuah wordplay
- Isa 13:6: shod/Shaddai — "devastation from the Almighty" = sound-play in Hebrew
"""
import json, pathlib
ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

ISAIAH = {
"9": {
"1": "<p>The opening verse reverses the darkness of chapter 8's closing: <em>no more gloom</em> where gloom once reigned. The MKT preserves the Hebrew contrast structure without softening it. The geographical references — Zebulun, Naphtali, the way of the sea — anchor the promise in the northern territories that fell first to Assyrian conquest, making the fulfillment in Matt 4:13-16 geographically precise.</p>",
"2": "<p><em>The people who walked in darkness have seen a great light.</em> The Hebrew <em>haalekh</em> (walking) is a participle indicating habitual action — they were characteristically darkness-walkers; the light-seeing is a prophetic perfect (seen as already accomplished). The MKT's past tense <em>have seen</em> captures this prophetic confidence. Matthew 4:16 cites this verse for Jesus' Galilean ministry.</p>",
"3": "<p>The joy-multiplication imagery draws on harvest and battle-spoil celebrations — the two moments in Israelite life when communal joy was most intense. The textual note: some manuscripts read <em>not</em> multiplied the joy (lo = no), while the Qere reads <em>to him</em> (lo = to him). The MKT follows the Qere, reading an increase of joy, which fits the surrounding context of abundance.</p>",
"4": "<p>The breaking of the yoke, staff, and rod evokes the Midianite defeat (Judg 7) where Gideon's 300 routed an overwhelming army. The MKT's <em>the day of Midian</em> is an allusion requiring the reader to know the Gideon narrative. The instrument of oppression — the rod — will become the instrument of the Messiah's rule in 9:6, but transformed from oppression into governance.</p>",
"5": "<p>Every warrior's boot and blood-soaked garment will be burned as fuel — an image of warfare's complete abolition. The MKT renders <em>sogar</em> as <em>soaked</em> rather than <em>rolled in</em> — the former emphasizes the saturation, giving visceral weight to the contrast with what follows. The burning of war equipment appears again in Ezek 39:9-10 for the eschatological end of warfare.</p>",
"6": "<p>Four throne-names in apposition: the MKT renders <em>Pele-Yoetz</em> as <em>Wonderful Counselor</em> (two words, not one name), following the majority reading. The name <em>Mighty God</em> (<em>El Gibbor</em>) uses <em>El</em> — the word for deity — applied to the royal child, a significant theological statement. <em>Everlasting Father</em> (<em>Abi-Ad</em>) means father of eternity/perpetuity — a protector-king role. <em>Prince of Peace</em> (<em>Sar-Shalom</em>) uses <em>shalom</em> in its full sense of well-being and wholeness, not merely absence of conflict.</p>",
"7": "<p>Three key terms cluster here: <em>mishpat</em> (justice/right order), <em>tsedaqah</em> (righteousness with social-justice force), and <em>shalom</em> (peace). The MKT renders <em>tsedaqah</em> as <em>righteousness</em> — a defensible choice, though the prophetic context (justice for the poor, governance of the oppressed) suggests the social-legal dimension is primary. <em>Olam</em> is rendered <em>everlasting</em> — absolute timelessness rather than age-long duration — following the NT application to Christ's eternal kingdom (Luke 1:33). The YHWH-name note applies: <em>the zeal of the LORD of hosts</em> identifies the divine personal name as the guarantor of this promise.</p>",
"8": "<p>The word (<em>dabar</em>) sent against Jacob — word as active agent of divine judgment, not mere communication. The MKT captures this with <em>sent a word</em> rather than <em>spoken against</em>: the word goes out and accomplishes its purpose (cf. Isa 55:11). The word-as-weapon motif will recur in 11:4 (<em>the breath of his lips</em>) and Rev 19:15.</p>",
"9": "<p><em>Yada</em> (know/acknowledge) is flagged as dispute-level 2. The verse says the people <em>know</em> — but in context it is a proud, self-sufficient knowing: <em>we know what to do to rebuild.</em> The MKT's <em>will know it</em> preserves ambiguity between simple awareness and the arrogant self-confidence Isaiah is critiquing.</p>",
"10": "<p>The bricks-to-dressed-stone / sycamores-to-cedars contrast illustrates the arrogance of upgrading rather than repenting after judgment. The sycamore was a common cheap timber; the cedar was the premium timber of temples and palaces. The people respond to God's corrective discipline with a building program, not a return to the LORD — a pattern Paul warns against in treating divine patience as license (Rom 2:4).</p>",
"11": "<p>The divine name YHWH is flagged here. <em>The LORD raises up the adversaries of Rezin</em> — the personal name of God as the one who orchestrates the nations is the MKT's way of maintaining the intimate, covenantal dimension of judgment. It is not an abstract deity but the covenant God who raises up enemies to discipline his people.</p>",
"12": "<p>Devoured with open mouth — the image of Israel as prey surrounded on all sides (Syrians in front, Philistines behind). The refrain <em>his hand is stretched out still</em> (repeated in 9:17, 9:21, 10:4) creates a structural urgency: the divine hand of judgment does not withdraw because the people do not return. The hand stretched out in judgment will be stretched out in healing and deliverance in 11:11.</p>",
"13": "<p><em>They have not returned to him who struck them, nor have they sought the LORD of hosts.</em> The failure of judgment to produce repentance is a recurring diagnostic in Isaiah (cf. 1:5). The divine name YHWH-Sabaoth (LORD of hosts) is flagged — the military title for the God who commands the armies of heaven, a title implying that Israel's enemies are ultimately fighting against the divine Commander of all armies.</p>",
"14": "<p><em>Head and tail, palm branch and reed</em> — the Hebrew idiom for high and low, top and bottom of society. All ranks will be cut off on a single day (<em>yom echad</em>). The day of comprehensive judgment is a precursor to the <em>Day of the LORD</em> theme developed in chapter 13. The divine name YHWH is flagged — this cutting-off is an act of the personal covenant God, not fate.</p>",
"15": "<p>The identification of the honored elder as the head and the lying prophet as the tail is a key hermeneutical moment: Isaiah is interpreting the metaphor. The false prophet who teaches lies is the most culpable part of the leadership structure — those who speak in God's name but do not speak God's truth bear the greatest responsibility for the people's misdirection (cf. Jer 23; Ezek 34).</p>",
"16": "<p><em>Those whom they lead are swallowed up.</em> The Hebrew <em>mevulshalim</em> means entangled, confused — the MKT's <em>swallowed up</em> is a stronger rendering that captures the total engulfment the false guidance produces. The young men and orphans and widows — the vulnerable who most need honest leadership — are specifically named as those the LORD will not have compassion on, a shocking reversal of divine mercy that underlines the severity of the crisis.</p>",
"17": "<p>The divine withholding of compassion on the young men and orphans is one of the most jarring statements in Isaiah. The MKT preserves the shock: <em>has no compassion</em> — not a softening like <em>cannot rejoice in</em>. In the context of 9:13 (they have not returned), this is the logical consequence: persistent refusal of repentance eventually exhausts the patience of the compassionate God. The refrain appears again.</p>",
"18": "<p>Wickedness burning like fire — an image that moves from individual wickedness to consuming societal conflagration. The briers and thorns of unproductive land catch first, then the dense forest, then the smoke rises in columns. The image of fire-as-judgment consuming first the worthless vegetation and then the great forest is developed in 10:17-19, where the Assyrian empire is the forest destroyed by the LORD's fire.</p>",
"19": "<p><em>Through the wrath of the LORD of hosts the land is scorched, and the people are like fuel for the fire.</em> The divine name YHWH-Sabaoth is flagged again. <em>Fuel for the fire</em> — the Hebrew <em>esh-oklah-esh</em> is a striking pun: fire is being consumed by fire. Society in breakdown devours itself. The MKT's <em>like fuel for the fire</em> preserves the consuming image without losing the self-devouring element.</p>",
"20": "<p>Snatch food on the right, eat on the left, still hungry — the insatiability of self-consuming sin. The tribal conflict that follows (Manasseh and Ephraim against each other and against Judah) is the domestic expression of the cosmic spiral of mutual destruction. When society forgets the LORD, it turns its violence inward. The refrain of the outstretched hand closes the chapter and opens it to 10:1.</p>",
"21": "<p>The closing refrain — <em>his hand is stretched out still</em> — is the third occurrence, creating a drumbeat of unrelenting divine attention. The hand that is stretched out in judgment is the same hand that will be stretched out for the second time in 11:11 to reclaim the remnant. The outstretched hand is the posture of both judgment and salvation; which you encounter depends on whether you turn toward or away from the LORD.</p>",
},
"10": {
"1": "<p><em>Woe to those who enact unjust laws.</em> The woe-oracle (<em>hoy</em>) opens chapter 10 with a direct address to the ruling class. The Hebrew <em>chaqaq</em> (enact/decree) is a technical legal term for official legislation — the critique is not of individual wrongdoing but of institutionalized injustice built into the legal system itself. This is system-level corruption, not personal sin alone.</p>",
"2": "<p><em>Turning the poor away from justice and robbing the rights of the afflicted.</em> <em>Mishpat</em> (justice/legal right) is the legal entitlement that the poor have by covenant law (Deut 24-25; Exod 22-23). The MKT's <em>rights</em> is strong — the poor have legal claims being actively suppressed. The oppressor is not merely neglecting the poor but perverting the legal system to strip them of what the Torah guarantees.</p>",
"3": "<p><em>The day of reckoning</em> (<em>yom pekudah</em>) — the day of visitation, inspection, or accounting. The MKT renders it <em>day of reckoning</em>, capturing the auditing metaphor: on that day the books will be opened and the corrupt rulers will have nowhere to put their unjustly acquired wealth. The rhetorical question — where will you flee? — parallels the Day of the LORD language of Amos 5:18-20.</p>",
"4": "<p><em>Nothing left but to cower among captives or collapse among the dead.</em> Two parallel fates: imprisoned or dead. The Hebrew presents the impossibility of escape from divine judgment. The refrain closes again: <em>his hand is stretched out still</em> — the fourth and final occurrence, showing that the woe-oracle against social injustice is the same divine hand at work as in the covenant judgments of chapter 9.</p>",
"5": "<p><em>Woe, Assyria — you are the rod of my anger; the club in whose hand is my fury!</em> A stunning reversal: Assyria, the most feared empire of the ancient Near East, is merely a tool in YHWH's hand. The <em>matteh</em> (rod/staff) and <em>maqqel</em> (club/stick) are implements — the metaphor fully worked out in 10:15 (the axe does not boast over the woodcutter). The MKT's <em>rod of my anger</em> and <em>club of my fury</em> maintain the double-object structure of the Hebrew.</p>",
"6": "<p>The LORD sends Assyria against <em>a godless nation</em> — Isaiah's own people. The Hebrew <em>chaneph</em> (godless/profane) is the same word used for those who have desecrated themselves. The covenant people are called godless for their covenant infidelity — a prophetic indictment that would have been as shocking to Isaiah's audience as Paul's declaration that Jews as well as Gentiles are under sin (Rom 3:9).</p>",
"7": "<p><em>That is not his intention.</em> The Assyrian king does not know he is fulfilling divine purposes — he acts from imperial ambition, not divine calling. This establishes the principle of secondary causation: human actors pursue their own goals while unknowingly fulfilling God's providential purposes. The NT applies this to the crucifixion (Acts 4:27-28) — the rulers acted from their own motives while fulfilling what God had predestined.</p>",
"8": "<p><em>Are not all my officers kings?</em> The Assyrian boast of imperial hierarchy — officers who are equivalent to kings in their power — illustrates the pride the MKT is about to deconstruct. The word <em>melech</em> (king) is flagged as dispute-level 2; in this context it functions as a superlative: my officers are as powerful as other nations' kings, implying Assyria's officers outrank everyone else's rulers.</p>",
"9": "<p>The list of conquered cities — Calno, Carchemish, Hamath, Arpad, Samaria, Damascus — is a catalogue of imperial conquests cited as precedents for the inevitable fall of Jerusalem. The rhetorical move is boastful induction: if all these have fallen, Jerusalem will too. Isaiah's point is that the boast contains its own refutation — Assyria's confidence in its track record is precisely the pride that will precede its fall.</p>",
"10": "<p><em>Just as my hand reached kingdoms whose idols surpassed those of Jerusalem.</em> The Assyrian king's idolatrous logic: if I could defeat nations with better idols, I can certainly defeat Jerusalem. He evaluates divine power by the quality of idol craftsmanship — the very category mistake Isaiah's idol polemic (44:9-20) deconstructs. The LORD is not an idol whose power can be assessed by comparison; he is the living God who raises up and tears down empires.</p>",
"11": "<p><em>Shall I not treat Jerusalem and her idols just as I treated Samaria and her carved images?</em> The Assyrian king's symmetry argument — Samaria fell; Jerusalem will fall by the same logic. The inclusion of idols in Jerusalem is historically accurate: under Ahaz and Manasseh, idolatry was practiced in the temple. Isaiah's response (v. 12) is that once YHWH has used Assyria, he will deal with Assyria's own arrogance.</p>",
"12": "<p><em>Once the Lord has completed his work on Mount Zion.</em> The <em>melech</em> (king) of Assyria is flagged — in context the proud heart and haughty eyes of the king. <em>The fruit of the arrogant heart of the king of Assyria</em> — the MKT renders this as the product/result of pride, making the king's internal attitude the target of divine judgment. The word <em>kavod</em> (glory/honor) is flagged in the surrounding verses — Assyria's glory is exactly what will be consumed (vv. 16-18).</p>",
"13": "<p><em>It is by my own power and wisdom that I have done this.</em> The Assyrian king's speech (vv. 13-14) is a masterpiece of self-aggrandizement: <em>I erased boundaries, plundered treasuries, subdued populations as easily as taking eggs from an abandoned nest.</em> The MKT preserves the first-person singulars throughout, which intensifies the arrogance: every verb is <em>I did</em>. The accumulation sets up the devastating axe-metaphor of v. 15.</p>",
"14": "<p><em>No one fluttered a wing, or opened a beak, or chirped.</em> The deserted nest metaphor — eggs taken without any resistance — is one of Isaiah's most vivid images of imperial ease. The three negatives (no wing-flutter, no beak-open, no chirp) emphasize total passivity of the conquered. The MKT preserves the avian vocabulary, which is essential for the rhetorical effect; <em>scooped up riches</em> captures the casual reach of empire.</p>",
"15": "<p><em>Does an axe boast over the person who wields it?</em> The tool-instrument metaphor: four instruments (axe, saw, rod, staff) and their absurdity if they claim agency over the person using them. The <em>kavod</em> (glory) in v. 16 is flagged — the Sovereign LORD will send a wasting disease on Assyria's <em>stout warriors</em> and will <em>kindle a blazing fire</em> under Assyria's <em>glory</em>. The MKT's <em>glory</em> captures the kabod's range from physical splendor to proud status.</p>",
"16": "<p><em>A wasting disease among the Assyrian's stout warriors.</em> The Hebrew <em>mishmanav</em> (stout ones/fat ones) is a description of the elite warrior class, well-fed and formidable. <em>Kavod</em> is flagged — rendered <em>glory</em>. Under the glory there will be kindled a fire like a burning flame. The image is of the brilliant exterior concealing the consuming fire that will hollow it out from within — divine judgment working from the inside.</p>",
"17": "<p><em>The Light of Israel will become a fire, and his Holy One a flame.</em> The divine titles here are striking: the LORD is Israel's Light (a positive presence-title, Ps 27:1) who becomes a consuming fire against Assyria (a judgment-title, Heb 12:29). Both attributes belong to the same God. The MKT preserves both titles without merging them into a generic deity. The fire consumes briers and thorns first — the worthless growth — then the great forest.</p>",
"18": "<p><em>It will consume the glory of his forest.</em> The <em>kavod</em> (glory) and <em>nefesh</em> (soul/life) are both flagged here. <em>Nefesh</em> in this context means the whole vitality — the MKT's <em>both root and branch</em> is a good rendering though it paraphrases. <em>It will be as when a sick man wastes away</em> — the Hebrew <em>mesos nasas</em> is a medical-deterioration image: the empire will not fall suddenly in battle but will waste away like a terminal illness.</p>",
"19": "<p><em>So few that a child could write them down.</em> From the dense impenetrable forest (the Assyrian army's metaphor) to a handful of trees a child can enumerate — total decimation described through the reversal of the forest imagery. The hyperbole (child counting) emphasizes the completeness of the reduction. This anticipates the remnant theology of 10:20-22: a small number surviving a massive catastrophe is both judgment and grace.</p>",
"20": "<p><em>In that day the remnant of Israel will no longer rely on him who struck them.</em> <em>Emet</em> (truth/faithfulness) is flagged — rendered <em>in truth</em>. The remnant will rely on the LORD <em>in truth</em> — in faithfulness, in genuine covenant loyalty rather than the formal religion that has characterized Judah. The turn from relying on Assyria (the instrument of discipline) to relying on the LORD who disciplines is the model of true conversion.</p>",
"21": "<p><em>A remnant will return — the remnant of Jacob — to the Mighty God.</em> <em>El Gibbor</em> (Mighty God) appears here — the same title used for the Messiah in 9:6. The remnant returns to the same Mighty God who is the Messiah's title, creating a theological echo: the one who rules on David's throne (9:7) and the one to whom the remnant returns (10:21) are identified by the same divine title.</p>",
"22": "<p><em>Only a remnant will return.</em> <em>Tsedaqah</em> is flagged — the decreed destruction is in <em>righteousness</em>. Paul cites this verse in Rom 9:27 as evidence that even in the OT, mere physical descent from Israel did not guarantee inclusion in the people of God — only the remnant is saved. The tension between numerical abundance (sand of the sea) and covenantal reality (only a remnant) is foundational for Paul's theology of election.</p>",
"23": "<p><em>The Lord GOD of hosts is executing his decreed destruction throughout the whole land.</em> The double title <em>Adonai YHWH-Sabaoth</em> emphasizes the triple sovereignty: master, covenant God, commander of armies. The destruction is <em>decreed</em> (<em>kalah ve-necheretset</em>) — cut, determined, inscribed in the divine plan. The MKT's <em>his decreed destruction</em> captures the irrevocability; this is not contingent judgment but fulfilled inevitability.</p>",
"24": "<p><em>O my people who live in Zion, do not be afraid of the Assyrians.</em> The same divine voice that decrees destruction now addresses his people with comfort — the same tension as the double edge of the outstretched hand. The divine name YHWH-Sabaoth addresses Zion as <em>my people</em> — the intimate covenant address in the midst of the judgment speech. The rod will be lifted, as at Midian (v. 26).</p>",
"25": "<p><em>For in a very little while my fury will be spent.</em> The temporariness of divine anger is a key Isaianic theme — anger is an instrument, not an attribute. The wrath against Judah passes through Assyria to expire; then the wrath turns against Assyria's arrogance. This double movement — through instrument to target — structures much of chapters 7-37: the LORD uses and then judges the nations he uses.</p>",
"26": "<p><em>The LORD of hosts will lash out against them as he defeated Midian at the rock of Oreb.</em> The divine name YHWH-Sabaoth is flagged. The Midian defeat (Gideon, Judg 7-8) and the Egyptian crossing are both cited as precedents for miraculous divine deliverance against impossible odds — the new Exodus typology that runs through Isaiah 40-55 begins here in chapter 10.</p>",
"27": "<p><em>The yoke will be lifted from your shoulders because of the anointing.</em> The Hebrew <em>lifney-shamen</em> is disputed: <em>because of fatness</em> (the yoke breaks because the ox's neck is too fat) or <em>because of anointing oil</em> (the Davidic anointing breaks the Assyrian yoke). The MKT's <em>because of the anointing</em> reads the messianic option, which connects to the anointed ruler of 9:6-7 and 11:1-5 — a defensible interpretation that makes the liberation messianic.</p>",
"28": "<p>Verses 28-32 are a dramatic march of an advancing army through Benjaminite territory toward Jerusalem — town by town, with trembling spreading as the army advances. The place-names are listed not for geographical instruction but for dramatic effect: the reader feels the inexorable advance through familiar places. The MKT preserves the place-name list without paraphrase, respecting the dramatic structure.</p>",
"29": "<p><em>At Geba they camp for the night; Ramah shakes with fear; Gibeah of Saul flees.</em> The shaking and fleeing of these towns creates a wave of terror that anticipates the final image at Nob. Each town mentioned is within sight of Jerusalem — the proximity is the terror. The MKT's active verbs (<em>shakes, flees</em>) are direct; some versions soften these to past tense narration, losing the dramatic immediacy.</p>",
"30": "<p><em>Cry out loudly, O daughter of Gallim! Listen, O Laishah!</em> The feminine address — daughter of Gallim — is a personification device common in the prophets (daughter of Babylon, daughter of Zion). The call to <em>listen</em> is urgent; the towns are being called to witness what is coming toward them, perhaps even to warn each other. The MKT's imperative forms preserve the urgency.</p>",
"31": "<p>Two more towns: Madmenah flees, Gebim's people scatter for cover. The escalating panic as the army approaches is Isaiah's way of making the reader feel the terror viscerally. The brevity of these verses — almost pure action verbs — mimics the speed and chaos of flight before an advancing army.</p>",
"32": "<p><em>That same day he will halt at Nob and shake his fist toward the hill of Zion.</em> Nob is within sight of Jerusalem — the military climax of the march. The gesture of shaking the fist is one of taunting threat, not action. At this precise moment (the next verse) the divine hand intervenes. The juxtaposition is dramatic: the Assyrian halts, threatens with a fist — and then the LORD lops off the branches with terrifying power.</p>",
"33": "<p><em>The Sovereign LORD of hosts is about to lop off the branches with terrifying power.</em> The divine name YHWH-Sabaoth is flagged. The divine Lumberjack suddenly appears at the moment of the Assyrian's triumph. The tall trees (<em>gavohim</em>) fall — the imagery of the great forest being cut down will become the stump of Jesse in 11:1. Judgment clears the forest so a new shoot can grow.</p>",
"34": "<p><em>He will slash down the dense forest with iron, and Lebanon will fall before a powerful one.</em> The chapter ends with the forest cleared — the imperial forest of Assyria reduced to stumps. This clears the narrative space for the next chapter's entirely different image: not a dense threatening forest but a single tiny shoot (<em>choter</em>) emerging from a stump. The contrast between 10:34 and 11:1 is one of Isaiah's most deliberate structural juxtapositions.</p>",
},
"11": {
"1": "<p><em>A shoot will come up from the stump of Jesse, and a branch from his roots will bear fruit.</em> The Hebrew <em>choter</em> (shoot) and <em>netzer</em> (branch) both denote small, unexpected new growth from what appears dead. Jesse (not David) is named — going back one generation to the pre-dynastic root, suggesting the Davidic dynasty will be cut to ground level and a new beginning made. Matt 2:23 cites <em>netzer</em> as a wordplay on Jesus' hometown of Nazareth (<em>Nazarenos</em>).</p>",
"2": "<p><em>The Spirit of the LORD will rest on him.</em> <em>Ruach</em> is flagged — the Spirit of wisdom, understanding, counsel, might, knowledge, and fear of the LORD. The sevenfold Spirit-endowment in the LXX became important for later theology (Rev 1:4's seven spirits). The MKT renders <em>ruach</em> as Spirit throughout, capitalizing it to indicate the divine Spirit. The verb <em>rest</em> (<em>nuach</em>) suggests settled, permanent resting — not a temporary charismatic endowment but an abiding presence (cf. John 1:32-33).</p>",
"3": "<p><em>He will take delight in the fear of the LORD.</em> <em>Shaphat</em> (judge) is flagged. The Messiah will not judge by appearances or rumors — by what he sees or hears — but by righteous judgment. YHWH is flagged as well. This inward, Spirit-driven judgment rather than surface-level assessment anticipates Jesus' refusal of external religious performance as the measure of righteousness (Matt 5:20; John 7:24).</p>",
"4": "<p><em>With righteousness he will judge the poor and with fairness he will decide for the afflicted.</em> <em>Ruach</em> is flagged — <em>the breath of his lips will strike the wicked.</em> The word (<em>dabar</em>) as weapon — spoken righteousness that executes judgment — is developed in NT as the sword from Christ's mouth (Rev 19:15) and the word of God sharper than any two-edged sword (Heb 4:12). <em>Shaphat</em> here carries forensic weight: legal decision for the poor as the beneficiaries of divine justice.</p>",
"5": "<p><em>Righteousness will be the belt around his waist, and faithfulness the girdle around his loins.</em> Clothing imagery for character — what girds the Messiah defines his identity. The MKT's <em>belt</em> and <em>girdle</em> distinguish the two parallel terms: <em>tsedaqah</em> (righteousness/justice) and <em>emunah</em> (faithfulness/steadiness). Paul's armor of God (Eph 6:14) draws on this: the belt of truth around the waist, developing the Isaianic image into the Christian life of warfare.</p>",
"6": "<p><em>The wolf will live peacefully with the lamb.</em> The Hebrew <em>gar</em> (sojourn as a guest/resident alien) — the wolf sojourns alongside the lamb as a guest-resident, not as a predator. The MKT's <em>live peacefully</em> captures the new relational status without importing full domestication. The reversal of predator-prey relationships is the eschatological sign of the age of the Spirit — creation renewed so that its enmities are healed.</p>",
"7": "<p><em>The cow and the bear will graze together; their calves will lie down side by side; and the lion will eat straw like the ox.</em> The dietary habits of the predators change — lion eating straw is the most radical transformation: the apex predator's nature is altered, not just its behavior. This is not merely peaceful coexistence but a change of what the creature fundamentally is — an image of thorough new-creation transformation.</p>",
"8": "<p><em>The nursing infant will play at the viper's burrow.</em> The most vulnerable human (infant) playing at the most dangerous animal (venomous serpent) without harm. The MKT's <em>nursing infant</em> and <em>toddler</em> make the human vulnerability concrete. The serpent-at-play image evokes the reversal of Eden (Gen 3:15): the enmity between the seed of the woman and the serpent is ended, but by the defeat of the serpent rather than a truce with it.</p>",
"9": "<p><em>Nothing will harm or destroy anywhere on my holy mountain, for the earth will be filled with the knowledge of the LORD as the waters cover the sea.</em> Two parallel images for comprehensive new-creation peace: (1) no harm anywhere on the holy mountain — the absence of violence; (2) universal knowledge of the LORD filling the earth as completely as water fills the ocean floor. YHWH is flagged — the divine name is the content of this universal knowledge. Hab 2:14 parallels this verse nearly exactly.</p>",
"10": "<p><em>In that day the Root of Jesse will stand as a banner for the peoples; the nations will seek him, and his resting place will be glorious.</em> <em>Kavod</em> (glory) is flagged — his resting-place (<em>menuchah</em>) will be glory. The Root of Jesse (not branch from Jesse's root, but Root — identifying him with Jesse's origin, not just his descendant) standing as a banner for <em>the peoples</em> (plural — Gentile nations) anticipates the global mission. Paul cites this in Rom 15:12 for Gentile inclusion in the covenant.</p>",
"11": "<p><em>The Lord will extend his hand a second time to reclaim the remnant of his people.</em> The second-time reclamation frames the new Exodus: as the first exodus brought Israel out of Egypt, the second brings back scattered exiles. The list of nations (Assyria, Egypt, Pathros, Cush, Elam, Shinar, Hamath, coastlands) suggests the entire known world will be the diaspora from which Israel is gathered. YHWH is flagged — the divine name as the agent of this second gathering.</p>",
"12": "<p><em>He will raise a banner for the nations and gather the exiled of Israel.</em> The banner (<em>nes</em>) of v. 10 is now raised by the Root of Jesse — the Messiah as the gathering-point for both Israel and the nations. The gathering imagery (gather, assemble) is the language of eschatological pilgrimage. In the NT, the cross becomes the banner that draws all people to Christ (John 12:32): lifted up, he draws all people to himself.</p>",
"13": "<p>The tribal jealousy between Ephraim and Judah — the two rival kingdoms — will end. The cutting-off of Judah's antagonizers and the joint military action against surrounding peoples (Philistines, Edomites, Moabites, Ammonites) envisions national reunification. For NT readers this is spiritualized: the enmity between Jew and Gentile is the deeper division resolved in Christ (Eph 2:14-16).</p>",
"14": "<p>The military imagery — swooping on the Philistines, plundering to the east — can be read as literally nationalistic or typologically as the spread of the gospel overcoming its adversaries. The MKT renders the geographical details accurately; the commentary note is that the NT spiritualizes the military conquest of Canaan into the spiritual warfare of 2 Cor 10:4-5.</p>",
"15": "<p><em>The LORD will dry up the gulf of the Egyptian Sea.</em> YHWH is flagged — the divine name as the one who dries the sea and waves his hand over the Euphrates to divide it into streams for walking through in sandals. The new Exodus typology is explicit: as Moses divided the sea (Exod 14), the LORD will divide both the Nile delta and the Euphrates to bring the scattered people home. The <em>ruach</em> (breath/spirit/wind) is flagged — the same breath/wind that divided the Red Sea (Exod 14:21) will work the new Exodus.</p>",
"16": "<p><em>There will be a highway from Assyria for the remnant of his people who survive, just as there was for Israel when they came up from Egypt.</em> The explicit first-Exodus / second-Exodus comparison closes the chapter. The highway through the wilderness (cf. Isa 40:3-5) is the path of the new-covenant community. John the Baptist cites this highway imagery (Luke 3:4-6 citing Isa 40:3-5) as preparation for Jesus' coming. The MKT's <em>highway</em> preserves the road-building imagery central to Isaiah's eschatological vision.</p>",
},
"12": {
"1": "<p><em>I praise you, O LORD; though you were angry with me, your anger has turned away and you have comforted me.</em> The YHWH-name is flagged — this is a personal address to the covenant God by name. The turning away of divine anger (<em>shub</em>) is the same verb for repentance — as Israel turns, God's anger turns away; as God's anger turns away, Israel can turn in praise. The MKT's <em>though you were angry</em> preserves the contrast that makes the praise meaningful: this is not cheap joy but joy after genuine judgment.</p>",
"2": "<p><em>The LORD, the LORD himself, is my strength and my song; he has become my salvation.</em> YHWH is flagged twice — the Hebrew reads <em>Yah YHWH oz v'zimrat</em>: the divine name appears in its short form <em>Yah</em> embedded in <em>salvation</em> (<em>yeshuah</em>) — this is the verbal root of the name Jesus (<em>Yeshua</em>). The MKT's rendering <em>he has become my salvation</em> preserves the verbal form. The verse is an almost verbatim quotation of the Song of Moses (Exod 15:2), framing the restoration as a new Exodus song.</p>",
"3": "<p><em>With joy you will draw water from the springs of salvation.</em> The springs of salvation (<em>ma'ayanei hayeshuah</em>) — salvation as water drawn from springs of divine life. The MKT preserves the Hebrew <em>yeshuah</em> (salvation) rather than substituting a synonym; the root of the name Jesus appears again. Jesus will develop this image: I am the living water (John 4:14; 7:38-39). Rev 7:17 closes the loop: the Lamb will lead them to springs of living water.</p>",
"4": "<p><em>Give thanks to the LORD; call on his name; make his deeds known among the peoples.</em> YHWH is flagged — the covenant name as the content of proclamation to the nations. <em>Yada</em> (know) is flagged — here <em>make known</em> (causative): Israel's calling is to publicize the divine name and deeds among the peoples. This missionary impulse — make God's deeds known to the nations — anticipates the Gentile mission of Acts (Acts 2:11; 13:47 citing Isa 49:6).</p>",
"5": "<p><em>Sing praises to the LORD, for he has done glorious things; make this known throughout all the earth.</em> <em>Yada</em> (know/make known) is flagged — again the causative: the knowledge of the LORD is to be <em>caused to be known</em> throughout the earth. The glorious things (<em>ge'ut</em>) are the specific acts of salvation — the new Exodus the previous chapter described. The MKT's <em>glorious things</em> is accurate; some versions use <em>excellent things</em>, but glorious better captures the weight of the Hebrew.</p>",
"6": "<p><em>Cry aloud and shout for joy, you who dwell in Zion, for great is the Holy One of Israel in your midst.</em> The chapter ends with the divine title <em>Qadosh Yisrael</em> (Holy One of Israel) — Isaiah's distinctive name for God, used 25 times in Isaiah, only 6 times in the rest of the OT. <em>Great</em> in your midst is the climax: the greatness of the Holy One is not an abstract attribute but a presence — he dwells in Zion. The NT equivalent is Immanuel: God with us.</p>",
},
"13": {
"1": "<p>The heading identifies this as an oracle (<em>massa</em>) — a word meaning both burden and lifting up/utterance. The double meaning is deliberate: the oracle against Babylon is a heavy burden on the prophet to carry, and a heavy word to pronounce. The MKT's <em>oracle</em> is standard; some preserve the weight dimension with <em>burden</em>. Isaiah the son of Amoz adds the prophetic credential — this is not speculative political analysis but divine revelation.</p>",
"2": "<p><em>Raise a banner on the bare mountain! Lift your voice to them! Wave your hand, so that they may enter the gates of the nobles.</em> The call to arms imagery — banner, voice, hand — is the language of mobilizing an army. The gates of the nobles are Babylon's famous fortified gates. The MKT preserves the military address without identifying the army — the effect is that the call comes before the caller is identified (v. 3: the LORD's consecrated troops).</p>",
"3": "<p><em>I have given orders to my consecrated troops.</em> The LORD speaks in the first person — the divine Commander addressing his <em>mequddashim</em> (consecrated/holy ones). This is not a standard army but a set-apart force — the same word used for the holy articles of the temple. The consecrated warriors become an instrument of divine judgment without themselves being righteous; they are set apart for the purpose of judgment as Babylon was once set apart for the purpose of disciplining Judah.</p>",
"4": "<p><em>The clamour of kingdoms, of nations massing together!</em> YHWH-Sabaoth is flagged — the LORD mustering the army of battle. The great noise of the mustering armies is described in terms of rumbling, roaring, clamor — all sound imagery that creates an auditory picture of overwhelming force assembling. The MKT's <em>LORD of hosts</em> preserves the military title; the Commander of heaven's armies is raising an earth-shaking force.</p>",
"5": "<p><em>They are coming from a distant land, from the far end of the heavens — the LORD himself and the weapons of his wrath.</em> YHWH is flagged — the divine name as the one who comes at the head of the instruments of wrath. The geographical scope (<em>far end of the heavens</em>) suggests cosmic rather than merely regional judgment. The Day of the LORD as cosmic event rather than local military campaign is the key claim here.</p>",
"6": "<p><em>Wail, for the day of the LORD is close at hand — it will come as devastation from the Almighty.</em> YHWH is flagged. The Hebrew sound-play is famous: <em>shod miShaddai yavo</em> — devastation from the Devastator will come. The MKT's <em>devastation from the Almighty</em> preserves the <em>Shaddai</em> title but loses the sound-play — an acceptable trade-off in English. The Day of the LORD (<em>yom YHWH</em>) is its first major occurrence in Isaiah, framing the oracle as eschatological rather than merely historical.</p>",
"7": "<p><em>At this every hand will go limp and every human heart will melt with fear.</em> The physical effects of divine judgment — limp hands, melting hearts — are the opposite of the courage described in 9:4 (the yoke of burden broken, the rod of the oppressor). When the LORD comes in judgment on the oppressor, even the oppressor's strength fails. The MKT's <em>go limp</em> and <em>melt with fear</em> preserve the bodily images of collapse.</p>",
"8": "<p><em>They will writhe like a woman in labor.</em> Birth-pang imagery for the suffering of divine judgment — the same image Jesus uses for the beginning of eschatological woes (Matt 24:8: all these are the beginning of birth pains) and Paul uses for creation's groaning (Rom 8:22). The MKT's labor imagery is consistent with NT use; the pangs of judgment become the pangs of the new creation being born.</p>",
"9": "<p>YHWH is flagged — the Day of the LORD described as <em>relentless in wrath and burning anger</em>. The day arrives with the purposefulness of a determined traveler; it cannot be deflected by the wicked's plans or preparations. The dual goal is stated: <em>to turn the land into a desolation and to banish its sinners from it</em>. Desolation of the land and banishment of sinners are the two coordinates of divine judgment in Isaiah's pattern.</p>",
"10": "<p><em>The stars of heaven and their constellations will not give their light; the sun will be darkened when it rises, and the moon will not shine.</em> The cosmic darkness of the Day of the LORD — astronomical signs that the ordering of creation is being shaken. Jesus cites the same cluster of images for the end of the age (Matt 24:29 citing Isa 13:10; also Joel 2:10-11; Amos 8:9). The MKT preserves the astronomical specifics (stars, constellations, sun, moon) without reduction to metaphor.</p>",
"11": "<p><em>I will punish the world for its evil and the wicked for their guilt.</em> The scope expands: the oracle against Babylon becomes an oracle against the world (<em>tevel</em>). Babylon is the world-empire; its judgment types the judgment of every world-empire that sets itself against God. The MKT's <em>world</em> (not <em>earth</em> alone) captures the universal scope of <em>tevel</em> — the inhabited world in its totality.</p>",
"12": "<p><em>Human life will become rarer than pure gold — rarer even than the gold of Ophir.</em> The scarcity of survivors expressed through the most precious metals. Ophir's gold was the gold of temple-construction quality (1 Kings 10:11) — the finest known. Human beings will become more rare than even this superlative standard of value. The MKT's <em>human life</em> (not merely <em>man</em>) is a good universalizing rendering.</p>",
"13": "<p>YHWH-Sabaoth is flagged — the cosmic shaking is an act of the LORD of hosts. The heavens tremble, the earth is displaced from its foundations. This language of cosmic de-creation (undoing the ordering of Gen 1) appears in NT apocalyptic (Heb 12:26-27 citing Hag 2:6; Rev 6:12-17). The MKT's <em>tremble</em> and <em>displaced from its foundations</em> are literal and accurate.</p>",
"14": "<p><em>Like a hunted gazelle or like sheep scattered with no one to round them up.</em> The individual turns to his own people and flees to his own land — the cosmopolitan empire dissolves into ethnic flight. The sheep-without-a-shepherd image (Matt 9:36; Mark 6:34) resonates here: when the shepherd-king of Babylon fails, the flock scatters. The MKT's double simile (gazelle + sheep) preserves the Hebrew parallelism.</p>",
"15": "<p><em>Anyone who is caught will be run through with a sword; anyone taken prisoner will fall by the sword.</em> The comprehensive violence of conquest — caught or captured, the outcome is the same. The rhetoric of no escape is deliberate: this is divine judgment executed through human agents, and its thoroughness is the point. No ransom, no escape, no exception for the powerful.</p>",
"16": "<p><em>Their children will be dashed to pieces in front of them.</em> One of the most disturbing verses in the OT — and one that Ps 137:9 reflects in reverse (the imprecation against Babylon). The practice was historical and documented in ancient warfare; Isaiah describes it not approvingly but as the horror that will befall Babylon what Babylon inflicted on others. The MKT preserves this without softening, which is important for honest engagement with the text's historical realism.</p>",
"17": "<p><em>I am rousing the Medes against Babylon — a people who care nothing for silver and feel no delight in gold.</em> The Medes as divine instrument are identified before they are aware of their appointment — the same pattern as Assyria in chapter 10. The Medes' indifference to treasure means they will not be bought off; they are a pure instrument of destruction. Historically, the Medes and Persians under Cyrus conquered Babylon in 539 BC.</p>",
"18": "<p><em>Their bows will cut the young men down; they will show no mercy on newborn infants.</em> The reversal of the Babylonian victimization of Israel (2 Kings 24-25) by exactly the same methods. The oracle operates on the lex talionis principle applied at the national level: what Babylon did to others will be done to Babylon. The MKT's <em>bows will cut down</em> is literal — arrows cutting through the young men.</p>",
"19": "<p><em>Babylon, the most glorious of kingdoms, the pride and glory of the Chaldeans, will be overthrown by God like Sodom and Gomorrah.</em> The <em>Elohim</em> title is flagged — the grammatically plural divine name with singular reference. The comparison to Sodom and Gomorrah is the ultimate standard of divine judgment: sudden, total, irreversible. Rev 18:2 applies this oracle to spiritual Babylon (Rome). The MKT's <em>God</em> renders <em>Elohim</em> as singular, following standard convention.</p>",
"20": "<p><em>It will never be inhabited or lived in through all generations.</em> The permanent desolation of Babylon is the sign of complete divine judgment. Historically, Babylon declined over centuries but was not immediately or completely desolated after 539 BC — which is why this oracle functions typologically in Revelation as describing the eschatological end of the world-empire principle that Babylon represents, not merely the historical city.</p>",
"21": "<p><em>Wild animals will rest there, and its houses will be full of howling creatures.</em> The reversal of Babylon's splendor into a haunt for wilderness animals — jackals, ostriches, wild goats, hyenas — is the standard prophetic image of complete urban collapse (also Jer 50-51). The list of animals in the MKT follows the Hebrew; some are difficult to identify precisely (<em>lilith</em> in v. 22 is rendered <em>night creature</em> or <em>screech owl</em>). The MKT's <em>howling creatures</em> captures the desolation-ambience.</p>",
"22": "<p><em>Her time is almost here and her days will not be prolonged.</em> The oracle closes with the urgency of near fulfillment — <em>almost here</em> (<em>karov</em>). The temporal urgency of prophetic oracles operates on both historical and eschatological levels: historically the fall of Babylon was imminent for Isaiah's audience two centuries later; eschatologically the fall of the world-empire system is always near for those who live under its oppression. Rev 1:3 opens with the same temporal urgency: <em>the time is near</em>.</p>",
},
}

def main():
    data = load_comm('mkt-original', 'isaiah')
    merge_comm(data, ISAIAH)
    chs = sorted(data.keys(), key=lambda x: int(x))
    total_v = sum(len(data[c]) for c in chs)
    print(f'Isaiah original: {len(chs)} chapters, {total_v} verses')
    save_comm('mkt-original', 'isaiah', data)

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
